<article class="why-article">
  <p class="why-meta">June 2026 · Chris Gilbert</p>
  <h1>Which model should you actually use?</h1>

  <div class="wm-tldr">
    <p class="wm-tldr-label">The short version</p>
    <p class="wm-tldr-intro">Staring at a model dropdown in Claude Code, Codex, Cursor or a chat app? You don't need token maths to make a good pick — almost every lineup is really just three tiers, and the names change but the trade-off doesn't:</p>
    <div class="wm-tier wm-tier-small">
      <span class="wm-tier-dot"></span>
      <span class="wm-tier-name">Small</span>
      <p class="wm-tier-body"><strong>Fast and cheap.</strong> Haiku, GPT-mini, Flash. Great for quick edits, search, simple Q&amp;A and high-volume routine work. The default you should reach for more often than you do.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="wm-tier wm-tier-mid">
      <span class="wm-tier-dot"></span>
      <span class="wm-tier-name">Mid</span>
      <p class="wm-tier-body"><strong>The all-rounder.</strong> Sonnet, GPT standard, Gemini Pro. The sweet spot for everyday coding, writing and answering questions over documents — good enough for most things without frontier prices.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="wm-tier wm-tier-frontier">
      <span class="wm-tier-dot"></span>
      <span class="wm-tier-name">Frontier</span>
      <p class="wm-tier-body"><strong>The smart, slow, pricey one.</strong> Fable, Opus, GPT's reasoning models. Worth it for hard, multi-step work — agentic coding, tricky debugging, deep analysis — where being a bit better each step compounds. Overkill — often <span class="num">10×</span> the cost of a small model — for the everyday stuff.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="wm-tldr-foot">Rule of thumb: <strong>start one tier lower than feels comfortable, and only move up when the cheaper model actually lets you down.</strong> The rest of this page is the longer version — task by task — and <%= link_to "the price table", root_path %> shows what each tier costs.</p>
  </div>

  <p>The most expensive habit in LLM engineering is using a frontier model for everything. It's an understandable habit — <%= link_to '"the good one" never gets you blamed', why_path %> — but the price spread between tiers is enormous: within Anthropic's own lineup, Claude Fable 5 costs <span class="num">10×</span> what Claude Haiku 4.5 does on every dimension, and across providers the gap between the priciest frontier model and the cheapest small one is more than <span class="num">300×</span>. A tier mismatch isn't a rounding error. It's the whole bill.</p>

  <p>The right rule is boring: <strong>use the cheapest model that passes your eval, and route up when it fails.</strong> No eval yet? Run the rule in reverse: prototype on a frontier model to find your quality ceiling, then walk down tiers until something breaks. Your eval is the arbiter, not this page and not a leaderboard. But you need somewhere to start, so here is my starting guess for the five most common task shapes — what tier is usually enough, and which price dimension actually dominates the cost, because it's often not the one on the sticker.</p>

  <h2>Classification and routing</h2>
  <p class="verdict">tier: small · cost driver: input price</p>
  <p>Labelling tickets, moderating content, routing requests — a paragraph or a page in, a token or two out. This is the task small models were built for: providers themselves position their smallest models for classification and routing. (A huge label taxonomy or subtle multi-label calls can push you up a tier — that's what the eval is for.) Because output is near-zero, <strong>input price is the entire bill</strong> — and small-tier input starts around <span class="num">$0.10</span> per million tokens. Running a frontier model here is paying a surgeon to take your temperature.</p>

  <h2>Data extraction to JSON</h2>
  <p class="verdict">tier: small–mid · cost driver: input price</p>
  <p>Pulling structured fields out of messy text. Small models handle typical schemas; step up to mid when the source is adversarial or a missed field is expensive. Deep nesting is a different problem — it trips up <em>every</em> tier, so simplify the schema before you upgrade the model. The metric that matters here is <strong>cost per accepted document, not cost per request</strong>: a cheap model that fails twice and needs human review isn't cheap. Output is short and mechanical, so input price dominates again — and extraction is the classic candidate for <strong>batch pricing</strong>, which halves the bill at most providers if you can wait minutes instead of seconds.</p>

  <h2>RAG answering</h2>
  <p class="verdict">tier: mid · cost driver: input price, then cached input</p>
  <p>Answering questions over retrieved documents. The retrieval does the hard part; the model mostly needs to read carefully and decline to invent. Mid-tier models are reliably good enough, and the economics are lopsided: you're feeding in thousands of tokens of context to get a paragraph back, so <strong>you're buying input tokens, overwhelmingly</strong>. If your system prompt and document set repeat across requests, cached-input pricing — typically <span class="num">4–10×</span> cheaper than regular input — changes which model wins.</p>

  <h2>Long-document summarisation</h2>
  <p class="verdict">tier: small–mid · cost driver: input price</p>
  <p>The most input-heavy shape there is: a hundred pages in, one out — so tier choice gets multiplied by every page you feed it. Cheap long-context models have made routine summarisation a small-tier task; pay for mid or above when missing a clause in the middle of page sixty actually costs you something — "lost in the middle" is reduced, not solved. And because summarisation is rarely latency-sensitive, it's the other natural batch-pricing candidate.</p>

  <h2>Agentic coding</h2>
  <p class="verdict">tier: frontier · cost driver: cached input, then output</p>
  <p>The exception, and it's a big one. Multi-step agents that read a codebase, plan, edit, and re-check compound their errors — a model that's 95% as good per step is far less than 95% as good after thirty steps. This is the task that earns frontier prices. (For the main loop, anyway — the emerging pattern is a frontier orchestrator delegating search and exploration to small-tier subagents.) The underappreciated part: agents re-send the same growing context on every step, so the overwhelming majority of what you buy is cache reads, and <strong>cached-input price matters more than headline input price</strong>. Two frontier models with the same sticker can differ sharply once caching enters the math — check the cached column on <%= link_to "the table", root_path %>, not just the first one.</p>

  <h2>The honest caveats</h2>
  <p>These are dated judgments, not benchmarks — I'll say "good enough for typical schemas," never "scores 87.2," and when the market moves (a mid model gets frontier-grade at coding, say) these verdicts get revised, visibly. The tier floor is also only half the decision: a "small" verdict still leaves more than a <span class="num">10×</span> spread between the cheapest and priciest small models, which is what <%= link_to "the table", root_path %> is for.</p>

  <p>And the other half — <em>"fine, mid tier for RAG, but what does that cost at my volume?"</em> — is the question this site exists to answer next. I'm building a <strong>cost calculator</strong>: pick a task shape like the ones above, set your volume, and get a ranked monthly bill across every model we track, at live prices, shareable as a link. Until then: start cheap, write an eval, and only pay frontier prices where the task actually earns them.</p>
</article>
